rect.title: Temperature is a property of an object that determines the direction of the net heat flow when it interacts with a second object or the environment.
When there is no net flow of heat between a hot body and the environment, the body is in thermal equilibrium. Both will have the same temperature.

The temperature scale are created by measuring the change in thermometric property (e.g. the length of mercury in glass column, resistance of wire) when placed in thermal equilibrium with standard points like melting point and boiling point of water.

The absolute scale of temperature is a theoretical scale that is independent of the properties of any particular substance. Two temperatures commonly used as a reference temperature 1) Absolute Zero, 2) Triple-Point of water.
Absolute zero is the temperature at which all substances have a minimum internal energy (NOT zero energy ). On the thermodynamic scale, it is assigned a value of 0 K.
The mole is the amount of substance that contains the same number of particles as the number of atoms in 0.012 kg (or 12g) of carbon-12.
An ideal gas is one that obeys the equation p V = n R T for all values of pressure, volume and temperature
The average kinetic energy of the molecules of an ideal gas is proportional to its thermodynamic temperature.
Avogadro constant (NA). It is thus the number of particles (atoms or molecules) in one mole of substance.
